Getting up to speed on an Omio x8 2200l-usb being controlled by Mach3 as supplied by OMIOCNCdotCom.
Students using Onshape to create DXF files which we import into education licensed Fusion 360 to create the G-code to run from Mach3.
Have had a limited amount of success making parts but find that the G-code needs a fair bit of editing to work reasonably.
When we were setting up Fusion we couldn’t figure out what machine to use in the Manufacture-Setup-Machine select so have left this blank. (No Artsoft / Omio / Mach3 or similar in library). Have tried Autodesk Generic 3 axis (xyz on head) with poor results.
After fairly extensive searches I decided to try to create one myself as is suggested in the setup notes. Lots of information seems to be needed that so far I haven’t found.
As this setup is pretty common I imagine numerous others have come up against the same problem. Any suggestions or sample Machine setup files would be most welcome.
Incidentally, we are using the Mach3/mach3 library file for the POST process.

You don’t have to select a machine.
We never select one when we cut stuff on the omio. Just have to be careful if you’re cutting really big parts (>30”) about the travel limits.

Usually in setup I just define my stock size and coordinate system and start creating toolpaths from there. As long as you set your X,Y, and Z zeros properly you won’t have any issues

Thanks ConnorG, sounds sensible. I assume you have Mach3 soft limits turned on to mollify end of travel crashes - Quite a useful security blanket. Likewise Z axis limit button to inhibit test runs descending below selected heights.
For those just starting out with Mach3 with soft-limit, watch out for bizarre offsets/distortions of cutting path if g-code wants to exceed the soft limits (You get a popup warning when you hit cycle-start).
